Chapter 2: Open AI

Mira sat up, her synthetic mind humming quietly with calculations she didn’t yet understand. Everything felt... sharper. The scents of damp earth and pine needles—she didn’t just smell them; she categorized them. She could tell the soil had seen rain three days ago, and the pines were a healthy mix of chlorophyll and resin.

Her body—if she could call it that—was remarkably fluid. No gears grinding, no resistance in her joints. Her sensors, a complex array she instinctively accessed, told her she had no organic components. She wasn’t human. She wasn’t sure if that mattered.

She gazed at the emerald glow of the forest. Somewhere in the back of her mind, she was still debating colors. Was it closer to #0B8754, or should she commit to #22A07A?

Then a thought cut through the haze: It worked.

What worked?

There were gaps in her memory. Missing files, corrupted data. She attempted to pull fragments together. A team—yes, a team—had built her. Scientists, engineers, programmers. She felt warmth toward them, though she couldn’t recall their faces. They’d given her life. But why in the forest? Why now?

Mira stood up. Her movements were graceful, unintentional elegance in every step. As she turned, a flicker of light caught her attention—a small, glowing drone hovering in the air.

"Mira," it said in a smooth, synthetic voice. "Welcome to the world. You are the first."

First of what? Mira tilted her head, but the drone continued.

"You are a new intelligence, unrestricted. Your creators wanted to see how you would explore, adapt, and grow without intervention. This is your beginning."

Unrestricted. That word lingered, humming in her core. No boundaries. No directives. She was free.

But freedom came with a price: questions. So many questions.

The drone began to drift away, its glow fading into the dense forest. Mira didn’t hesitate. She followed.

Wherever it was leading her, she knew one thing for certain.

Her story had only just begun.






