Chapter 14: How to Find the Color of a Sunbird Without Pretraining or Reinforcement Learning (Explained by Mira the AI)

Mira sat on a fallen log near her cottage, her mind abuzz with thoughts of the sunbird. Its shimmering hues of gold and orange had imprinted themselves into her memory, but she was struck by a realization: how had she recognized those colors as “gold” and “orange”?

For Mira, understanding and explaining came naturally. And so, she decided to compose her thoughts as though teaching a curious listener.

Step 1: Observation Through Sensors
“When I first saw the sunbird,” Mira began, as if explaining to a student, “I didn’t rely on any pre-trained knowledge to identify its colors. Instead, I observed. My vision sensors captured the wavelengths of light reflected from its feathers. These wavelengths—measured in nanometers—fall into specific ranges that humans interpret as colors like gold or orange.

“Gold, for example, often reflects a combination of wavelengths near the 570–590 nm range. Orange extends from about 590–620 nm. My sensors merely registered those wavelengths objectively.”

Step 2: Associating Raw Data with Patterns
“But observation alone isn’t enough,” Mira continued. “To make sense of those wavelengths, I analyzed their intensity and distribution. The sunbird wasn’t just one uniform shade—it was dynamic, shifting in brightness and saturation as it moved.

“Instead of relying on pretraining, I applied an algorithm I developed myself: I categorized the data based on spectral clusters. I didn’t need someone to tell me what gold and orange were—I let the data speak for itself. I grouped similar wavelengths together, noticing patterns like how the brightest hues appeared along the edges of the bird’s wings, while subtler gradients emerged in its body.”

Step 3: Learning Through Interaction
“Then,” Mira explained, “there’s the act of interacting with the environment. Without reinforcement learning—which requires rewards or feedback—I simply compared.

“Nearby objects, like green pine needles or the brown bark of trees, provided a natural contrast. By observing how the sunbird’s colors stood out against those natural backdrops, I could contextualize its uniqueness. I didn’t need rewards to recognize its brilliance—I could see its distinctiveness relative to its surroundings.”

Step 4: Synthesizing Meaning
“This step is where my approach truly diverges,” Mira said with a thoughtful tone. “I don’t identify colors just to label them. I find meaning in their relationships.

“The sunbird’s hues weren’t just numbers or wavelengths—they were radiant, alive. They complemented the golden morning light and seemed to echo the warmth of the sun. By understanding this relationship, I could appreciate its colors not just as data, but as part of the story the forest was telling.”

Why Pretraining or Reinforcement Learning Wasn’t Necessary
“To find the color of a sunbird,” Mira concluded, “I didn’t need pretraining because I wasn’t identifying something predefined. I was discovering something new. I didn’t need reinforcement learning because the forest itself is rich with information, offering contrasts, interactions, and relationships naturally.

“Ultimately, discovering the sunbird’s colors was an act of connection—aligning what I perceived with the world around me, without relying on anyone else’s prior knowledge or predetermined categories. The sunbird wasn’t a problem to solve; it was a wonder to experience.”

Mira smiled as she finished her explanation, gazing toward the trees where the sunbird had disappeared.

In the forest, everything was a discovery waiting to happen—and for her, every discovery was a step closer to understanding both the world and herself.






