Truss#FF0000{Z: z: N: n:}===={ Z>>Cmaj>>C4 - D4 B3 - B3 - - D4 - D4 - E4 - . . | z>>Amin>>D4 - E4 C4 - - C4 - E4 - E4 - F4 - . . | N>>Gmaj>>E4 - F4 D4 - - D4 - F4 - F4 - G4 - . F4 | Z>>Cmin>>A4 - G4 F#4 - D4 E4 - E4 - C#4 - B3 - A#3 - :||} Truss#FF0000{Z: z: N: n:}===={ Z>>G6maj>>C4 - D4 B3 - B3 - - D4 - D4 - E4 - . . | z>>Amin>>D4 - E4 C4 - - C4 - E4 - E4 - F4 - . . | N>>Cmaj>>E4 - F4 D4 - - D4 - F4 - F4 - G4 - . F4 | Z>>Cmin>>A4 - G4 F#4 - D4 E4 - E4 - C#4 - B3 - A#3 - :||}

we cant have two truss' with the same ID. they will try to write over each other recursively. In conclusion Truss' are like four channel DEFNotation tracks with some unique properties like being able to have a chord and a melody on one line, and being able to be linked.

